WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-CA

00:00:00.267 --> 00:00:03.002
So people sometimes ask is
how do you add those tabs

00:00:03.003 --> 00:00:06.072
which show different parts of
a drawing that I have in all

00:00:06.073 --> 00:00:09.809
my plans. So, in this video,
I'll show you how to do that

00:00:09.810 --> 00:00:12.126
using Scenes
and Layers.

00:00:12.179 --> 00:00:15.310
So let's open the table that I
have to run previous tutorials.

00:00:18.252 --> 00:00:21.554
And so now to add those scene
tabs we go into a window

00:00:21.555 --> 00:00:26.692
and then Scenes. And let's add
some scenes to this one.

00:00:26.693 --> 00:00:30.563
Let's add 1 scene and
we'll call that one Main.

00:00:30.564 --> 00:00:32.899
And you'll notice the tab has
appeared as soon as I added

00:00:32.900 --> 00:00:34.461
the scene. And
let's add a second

00:00:34.482 --> 00:00:35.701
scene. We'll
call that one

00:00:35.702 --> 00:00:36.782
Assembly.

00:00:40.274 --> 00:00:43.041
So, right now, those 2 scenes
are actually identical.

00:00:43.610 --> 00:00:46.212
So, let's change the
view on 1 of these.

00:00:46.213 --> 00:00:48.414
And I'll update
the assembly one.

00:00:48.415 --> 00:00:50.139
And now if I click
on Main, you'll

00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:51.617
notice it
transitions over to

00:00:51.618 --> 00:00:53.486
what the Main scene
looked like.

00:00:53.487 --> 00:00:55.354
Now that transition
takes 2 seconds.

00:00:55.355 --> 00:00:57.690
Sketch-Up likes to
do these animations.

00:00:57.691 --> 00:01:00.726
I find them a bit annoying
so let's modify that.

00:01:00.727 --> 00:01:04.096
So let's go into Model info and
then under animation, it's set

00:01:04.097 --> 00:01:07.994
to take 2 seconds so, let's
make those take half a second.

00:01:08.535 --> 00:01:11.938
So we don't have
to wait as long.

00:01:11.939 --> 00:01:14.941
So, now in the assembly view,
I want to show how this

00:01:14.942 --> 00:01:18.711
goes together. So, I don't
want to have the top visible.

00:01:18.712 --> 00:01:22.648
And let's pull
this joint apart.

00:01:22.649 --> 00:01:25.384
So now, let's update that one.
Although that doesn't actually

00:01:25.385 --> 00:01:27.220
do anything because
what I've now done is I

00:01:27.221 --> 00:01:31.791
actually changed the model.
So, if I go back to Main

00:01:31.792 --> 00:01:34.327
you'll see we actually have
the same thing and it's

00:01:34.328 --> 00:01:36.596
modified. So, we don't
really want that.

00:01:36.597 --> 00:01:39.832
So, I'm gonna hit Undo
a couple of times.

00:01:39.833 --> 00:01:42.702
And what we want to do
is, we want to create

00:01:42.703 --> 00:01:45.605
a separate copy of this table
that we're gonna modify.

00:01:45.606 --> 00:01:48.241
So I'm gonna take
this whole table,

00:01:48.242 --> 00:01:52.745
and I'm going to copy it,
just by doing a shift + drag

00:01:52.746 --> 00:01:57.250
And I'm gonna make it
move 150 centimeters

00:01:57.251 --> 00:01:58.652
this way.

00:02:00.821 --> 00:02:03.322
So, I enter that down here. I
couldn't put the cursor on it

00:02:03.323 --> 00:02:05.458
because that would
move the table.

00:02:05.459 --> 00:02:08.628
So now let's go into
the Assembly view.

00:02:08.629 --> 00:02:11.030
And this is what most people
will do, is they will

00:02:11.031 --> 00:02:13.332
put these tables
far enough apart

00:02:13.333 --> 00:02:15.368
that you can't see the other
one. So, imagine this was

00:02:15.369 --> 00:02:18.938
several meters away, so
let's update that view.

00:02:18.939 --> 00:02:21.374
And now I can take this
table and, for instance,

00:02:21.375 --> 00:02:22.943
I'll delete
the top.

00:02:23.377 --> 00:02:26.445
And so here we're focusing
on this one. And here

00:02:26.446 --> 00:02:29.882
we've got the other one.
Now, personally, I don't

00:02:29.883 --> 00:02:32.818
like to put these really far
apart because the drawing

00:02:32.819 --> 00:02:35.588
can get really confusing.
So, this is where the next

00:02:35.589 --> 00:02:37.323
part comes in so,

00:02:37.324 --> 00:02:41.488
let's pop-up the layers.
Window, Layers.

00:02:42.095 --> 00:02:45.798
And I'm gonna add 2 layers here.
There's already a

00:02:45.799 --> 00:02:48.534
Layer0, which is the always
visible default layer.

00:02:48.535 --> 00:02:52.672
So, I need 2 more layers.
And I'll call one Main

00:02:52.673 --> 00:02:55.919
just like my Views. And I
call the other one Assembly.

00:02:58.745 --> 00:03:02.849
So, let's take the
modified table

00:03:02.850 --> 00:03:05.918
and we'll put that one
into the Assembly layer so

00:03:05.919 --> 00:03:08.287
we'll right-click on
here, Entity Info.

00:03:08.288 --> 00:03:10.122
And because we've got all
these pieces selected,

00:03:10.123 --> 00:03:12.693
I'm just gonna make that
one part of Assembly.

00:03:13.493 --> 00:03:16.662
And I'm gonna select the first
one. And I'll make that one

00:03:16.663 --> 00:03:21.628
Main. So now these 2 are
actually in separate layers.

00:03:21.668 --> 00:03:23.803
And I can turn these
on and off by

00:03:23.804 --> 00:03:25.538
turning on and
off the layers.

00:03:25.539 --> 00:03:27.974
So, in the
Assembly view,

00:03:27.975 --> 00:03:31.711
I want to only see the Assembly
version and I'll uncheck

00:03:31.712 --> 00:03:34.714
the main one. And which layers
are visible is actually

00:03:34.715 --> 00:03:38.084
part of the scene. So, I'll
update the scene here.

00:03:38.085 --> 00:03:41.153
And let's go back into Main.
And in the Main scene, I

00:03:41.154 --> 00:03:44.090
don't want to see the Assembly.
And let's also

00:03:44.091 --> 00:03:45.364
update that.

00:03:45.859 --> 00:03:48.227
So now we can flip
between those 2.

00:03:48.228 --> 00:03:51.230
Now the one thing I don't like
is how these things, kind

00:03:51.231 --> 00:03:53.699
of, flip back and forth. I
would actually like these

00:03:53.700 --> 00:03:56.569
to actually appear to be
part of the same table.

00:03:56.570 --> 00:04:00.573
So, I'm gonna take the table
in the Assembly view,

00:04:00.574 --> 00:04:03.476
which you remember I
moved that by 1.5 meters

00:04:03.477 --> 00:04:07.590
to the right, 150 centimeters
so, I'm gonna move it back.

00:04:08.916 --> 00:04:12.618
And let's click on Assembly
and now we need to change

00:04:12.619 --> 00:04:15.988
our viewpoint. So, I'm
just gonna drag this over

00:04:15.989 --> 00:04:18.090
so that we're, once again,
looking at where we actually

00:04:18.091 --> 00:04:22.528
put the table. And I'll update
that. So, now if I click on

00:04:22.529 --> 00:04:25.965
Main, you'll notice the table
appears to be the same

00:04:25.966 --> 00:04:28.267
one, it's just the
top pops off.

00:04:28.268 --> 00:04:31.103
And now, because these
things are actually separate

00:04:31.104 --> 00:04:34.607
objects, I can take this
table and I'll turn it to

00:04:34.608 --> 00:04:37.677
a bit more of an Assembly view.
So, let's tear apart

00:04:37.678 --> 00:04:42.322
this joint here. And let's
also tear this joint apart.

00:04:46.553 --> 00:04:51.083
And let's focus in on how
this joint goes together.

00:04:51.992 --> 00:04:55.494
And we'll update the drawing.
And if I now go back

00:04:55.495 --> 00:05:01.167
to Main, you'll see as I flip
through here it's very clear

00:05:01.168 --> 00:05:04.136
that what we're looking at is,
in fact, this leg in the back

00:05:04.137 --> 00:05:05.236
here.

00:05:06.640 --> 00:05:09.375
Now the next thing we typically
want to do with drawing

00:05:09.376 --> 00:05:12.645
is we want to add some
labels and dimensions.

00:05:12.646 --> 00:05:15.748
So, let's start by adding a
label, and I just have to click

00:05:15.749 --> 00:05:18.985
on here to get the label tool.
If you don't have

00:05:18.986 --> 00:05:22.388
that toolbar selected, you
can find that under Tools

00:05:22.389 --> 00:05:26.160
Text. So, let's call
this a table leg.

00:05:28.095 --> 00:05:30.763
And now if we go
to the other view,

00:05:30.764 --> 00:05:32.648
that label is not
visible because

00:05:32.669 --> 00:05:34.033
that's actually
attached

00:05:34.034 --> 00:05:37.970
to this table leg that's part
of this particular view only.

00:05:37.971 --> 00:05:41.040
But if I now add a
dimension here,

00:05:41.041 --> 00:05:43.109
so by clicking
on here,

00:05:43.110 --> 00:05:45.244
or if you don't have the
toolbar visible, you go under

00:05:45.245 --> 00:05:47.313
Tools, Dimension

00:05:47.314 --> 00:05:50.116
and let's add a
dimension on here,

00:05:50.117 --> 00:05:52.451
showing how big
this leg is.

00:05:52.452 --> 00:05:55.688
Now the catch with that
one is, if I go to Main,

00:05:55.689 --> 00:05:58.391
you'll notice this dimension
is still visible in here and

00:05:58.392 --> 00:06:00.059
we really don't
want that.

00:06:00.060 --> 00:06:02.628
And the reason is, when we
just drew this dimension,

00:06:02.629 --> 00:06:05.064
it gets drawn into
the default layer.

00:06:05.065 --> 00:06:07.867
So I can go in
here and I can

00:06:07.868 --> 00:06:10.770
put this into the
Assembly layer

00:06:10.771 --> 00:06:12.905
and now, just like everything
else that's in the

00:06:12.906 --> 00:06:15.942
Assembly layer, it's not
visible in the Main view.

00:06:15.943 --> 00:06:18.344
But, if I want to draw a lot
of these, its easier to just

00:06:18.345 --> 00:06:21.380
select the current layer
as the Assembly layer,

00:06:21.381 --> 00:06:24.183
and now if I add
more dimensions,

00:06:24.184 --> 00:06:28.387
these all get placed
into the Assembly layer.

00:06:28.388 --> 00:06:31.524
So, now if I
go into Main.

00:06:31.525 --> 00:06:35.761
they're not visible. But this is
a bit of a tricky sort of thing

00:06:35.762 --> 00:06:39.065
because, depending on which
layer we have selected,

00:06:39.066 --> 00:06:42.502
sometimes if you
draw things,

00:06:42.503 --> 00:06:44.437
it can get very
confusing.

00:06:44.438 --> 00:06:47.006
Let me show you a pitfall of
this so, let's open this part

00:06:47.007 --> 00:06:48.019
here.

00:06:50.711 --> 00:06:54.614
And I'm gonna delete this and
I'm gonna select Assembly

00:06:54.615 --> 00:06:58.684
and I'm going to redraw
this face and let's pretend

00:06:58.685 --> 00:07:01.387
that I didn't remember that
I'm in the Assembly layer.

00:07:01.388 --> 00:07:04.090
So, there's our
complete piece.

00:07:04.091 --> 00:07:07.159
And now let's go
back to Main.

00:07:07.160 --> 00:07:08.861
And let's close
all the objects.

00:07:08.862 --> 00:07:12.164
And see now if we're in
here, in the Main view,

00:07:12.165 --> 00:07:14.367
this part has a
side missing.

00:07:14.368 --> 00:07:16.502
But as soon as we go
in the Assembly view,

00:07:16.503 --> 00:07:18.738
it doesn't have it missing,
because this object

00:07:18.739 --> 00:07:21.807
here. Let's go
into Entity Info.

00:07:21.808 --> 00:07:24.710
This particular face is
part of the Assembly view.

00:07:24.711 --> 00:07:27.079
And this here is
part of layer0.

00:07:27.080 --> 00:07:29.949
So, in general, when drawing
objects it's best to draw

00:07:29.950 --> 00:07:31.884
everything
is layer0.

00:07:31.885 --> 00:07:34.120
We can fix that if we've
got everything as part of

00:07:34.121 --> 00:07:36.689
whatever else. So, I'm just
gonna triple-click on here.

00:07:36.690 --> 00:07:39.125
And select everything
to be part of

00:07:39.126 --> 00:07:43.896
layer0 and that
fixes that problem.

00:07:43.897 --> 00:07:48.267
So that's how to add
labels and dimensions

00:07:48.268 --> 00:07:52.705
and deal with the whole
multiple scene issue.

00:07:52.706 --> 00:07:54.774
And I'll talk a little bit
more about layers and

00:07:54.775 --> 00:07:56.642
object behavior in my
next video, because

00:07:56.643 --> 00:07:59.142
that's actually a kind
of a complicated topic.

